[6826491]

For those who don't already know, it's very much sanctionable to end a ship early, if your goal is to join a community jump. Don't do it. It's judged as a cross between a surrender and a suicide, that just so happens to take the rest of the crew with them. Community jumps are not worth the risk of a quarantine, and we judge such cases harshly. You don't want to earn a reputation for being someone who will screw over an ongoing ship to join a Community Jump, only to be quarantined on the Community Jump ship.

As for this ship: It's not a victory, if you ask me. The game was over before could it even begin, and I would strongly discourage anyone from trying to "outdo" this ship. In effect, this can't be declared a human victory, because the other team didn't even exist. The game isn't considered to have officially begun until the moment of Mush selection, so it doesn't count.

In regards to the Gold days: They count down at the start of every day you're on a ship. If you die (or your previous ship ends) and you join a ship at any point before the very next day change on that ship, a Gold day will NOT be deducted yet. The next time a Gold day will be deducted will be at the start of the next C1. Yes, that does mean that if you join a ship in C8, you'll still lose a Gold day the following cycle.

If you wait long enough (i.e. past the next day change,) you'll definitely have a Gold day deducted, regardless of when in the day you join the ship. This is why I try to join ships in what should be C2. There are two "timelines" of ships in play, offset by a cycle, and I don't want to accidentally join a ship in C8.

[7950824]

Hilarious, GT. Love it. I just wanted to chime in about the 'discussion' around the idea of removing the last O2, when someone is going to die at cycle change anyway, 'should you or should you not remove that capsule'.

It actually depends on your motivation. In itself that is not an inherently wrong action to take. Spazticus is specifically focusing on the motivation for taking that last O2, and that is key.

There are human-helpful strategies that can involve holding the last O2, and if your intentions are lawful, you're not likely to run into problems especially if your reasoning can be understood. An example (and felt like a win in its own right):

Human team was trying to kill the last known mush and having a very hard time to do so. We were almost out of air, had very few active players, but had a human tech/physicist with a little AP who had to go offline for a few cycles. I desperately wanted that Raluca to take one of our last few O2, or even 2 of them, because if we lost Raluca we lost all chance to get back to Sol, but we couldn't rush Pilgred with that mush alive. Raluca went offline without the O2, drat.

We got the mush dead and were waiting, hoarding AP to try and be there to rush Pilgred when Raluca reconnected. We ended up burning through all but one O2, Raluca had not yet come back. I took that last O2, because I was active most cycles, and could be there if needed to trade resets with Raluca, and was also commander to immediately jump us back when possible.

It also helped reduce the odds of Raluca dying, very slightly. There were about 6 alive at that point; if I let that O2 be destroyed, someone would die. If that someone was not Raluca, Raluca faced a 1/5 chance of dying the cycle after.

If any of us took that O2, then there was a 1/6 chance that cycle change would burn that O2, meaning that next cycle change Raluca faced a 1/6 chance of dying. Low, low odds, but it was slightly better than the alternative. Best would have been if Raluca had agreed to take the O2 before she had to go offline. Even though we would have started to suffocate sooner, we needed her alive to get back to Sol for a human win. Anything that improved the odds of her being alive still by the time she could log back in (and of course she needed someone alive to reset her, and somehow someone with enough AP to get back to Sol, hacking if needed) was good for the human team.... our only hope really of winning.


So it is not the action of taking the last O2 from the tank that is wrong. Motivation is the key, if you appear to be doing it for purely selfish or harmful to your team's goals reasoning, you do run some risks of being sanctioned if reported. If you can work a strategy for your side that uses that action in a pro-your-team fashion, you're doing the right thing.

[7950824]

There's even a couple other tiny advantages to holding the last O2 - if scraps are gathered after the cycle suffocation starts, and a capsule with 1 O2 gained.... you need 2 O2 to prevent suffocation for a cycle change.

If the last O2 had been allowed to be consumed, then you'd only have one O2 to decide if you should put into the tank or not - doing so won't prevent a death.

If the last O2 was held, both can be put in the tanks and one more cycle without any deaths can happen (and then the last O2 can be taken out again, holding against hope and chance).

If your ship has 'people who could fix the problem', which is probably rare, but they are not online then, it's probably better for anyone to take that last O2 than to let it be lost; it can even be passed around by being briefly put back into the tank and taken out by someone else.

However, if you experience a situation on your ship that looks like it is breaking the rules, report the person and explain what you think is rulebreaking. If a player were to state "I am taking the last O2 because I want to be Last man standing and Last Commandant so none of you can have it" and be reported for playing selfishly, well.

Playing selfishly is not actually against the rules. Playing against your team is, and many other things are, but cooperation is not actually a required thing, if the 'non-cooperation' is done in a way that does not break rules. Note that it is very easy for selfish, non-cooperative behavior to also break rules, but the part that breaks the rules is not that it is selfish or non-cooperative. A comment like that above could be part of being passively negative; put downs, hostility to the game and others, being so unpleasant that you make your ship an unenjoyable experience for others on it... that's sanctionable. But that's a pattern of behavior, a single comment like this example... To me that's not sanctionable.

If we can see how that player taking that last O2 worsened the odds for their team to win, that's a very different situation. If you see that happening on your ship, definitely do report it, and make sure to tell us what you know, how it hurts that player's team to make sure we understand what you do and know what to look for.

Here's a story I just have to share about a very strange ship that happened a while ago... My recollection's a bit fuzzy because of that, especially the beginning/middle bits, but here's what I can remember.

http://mush.twinoid.com/theEnd/9110

I woke up as Terrence, and everything seemed normal at first... until Raluca announced that she had built the sofa in her own turret. Before mush selection, if I recall correctly, and without really getting the okay from everyone else first. It turned out to be fine in the end, though, as we had the lizaro jungle and a second sofa blueprint which we installed on the bridge.

Things got even stranger when we found out that Raluca was hoarding Schrodinger and other items in said turret, making it into a den fit for a crazy cat lady. They were mostly useless items like the old T-shirt, the mad kube, and the commander's manual, but there were a couple of rations and space capsules for herself, and even the microwave. She still wasn't really hurting anybody, and admittedly it was rather nice to have our Phys/Tech Raluca capable of doing so much around the ship.

But it went downhill fast. There were too many inactive and inattentive humans, and we ended up getting barely anything done. Humans were killing each other out of desperation. One cycle I logged in to find out that there were 4 Mush on the crew bar. Gioele rampaged at some point, even taking the grenade blueprint and using one of the last few oxygen on it.

We somehow managed to kill two of them. I was convinced that we had no chance to survive, so when I saw two dots in Raluca's turret, I headed there immediately with full AP, thinking I could at least off one of them before my inevitable death. As it turned out, that other dot was Janice having just comforted Raluca a bunch of times. I knew it would look really bad if I didn't do something... But it was nearing the end of the cycle and she hadn't left yet, which was reason enough for me to kill her anyway. She could always be using that as cover for a conversion, after all.

My gut wrenched in horror as I found out that Janice was human. I found two oxygen capsules in the turret, so I brought them to the oxygen tank with the last of my points in an attempt to jury-rig this ship together for as long as I could. I recall having to drop my iTrackie somewhere along the line, so before I left, I explained my justification for killing Janice to Raluca in a private chat. It was the best I could do.

Cycle change happened and we were left with 4 oxygen. Four people were alive in total, two of them mush. I sat in the storage room, 1 AP/MP, unable to communicate. I had pretty much abandoned all hope by that point.

Suddenly, Raluca entered the room. She told me I was the only person she could trust, and that she had a plan to kill off the last two mush, blitz Pilgred, and return to Sol. She took two oxygen capsules and ordered me to take the other two. With luck, the mush would stay inactive, thinking their work was well done, and they'd suffocate. I had nothing to lose at that point, so I trusted her.

When we had the oxygen, she walked me back to her turret. I microwaved a ration and ate it, and we relayed Pilgred a few times. She told me to take the turret sofa. My morale was critical, but the cat (which I had yet to pet) was still in her turret. This allowed me to live through the suffocation deaths. Sure enough, over the next couple of cycles while the mush choked, we managed to stay coordinated enough to finish Pilgred. I was flabbergasted. Everything Raluca had done since the beginning of the game: building the sofa, keeping the cat, hoarding things... without it, this plan would not have been remotely possible.

On the final cycle, with just the two of us alive, Raluca became the commander and gave me one final mission. A last request that would bring closure to our impossible victory. A vivid blush played across her face as she invited me into her turret for a bit of... celebration.

Unfortunately, I couldn't react fast enough. Perhaps she was too flustered, or too eager to make the trip to Sol, or a combination of the two; she left for the bridge just 5 minutes later. My emotions were a confused blend of relief and regret. It was all I could do to silently load the fuel and await The End. I think mine and her final words sum it up quite nicely.

But yeah! That was easily the most unconventional game of Mush I've ever played, not to mention the most satisfying.
